            . I am a Bow-street patrol. I know the house No. 84, Fleet-street, City - the name of</p>
               <p>"R. Carlile" is over the door. On the 11th of May I went into the shop, and saw the defendant behind the counter; I asked if he had got</p>
               <p>"Paine's Age of Reason;" he said, Yes. I said,</p>
               <p>"Let me have it;" he put it into my hands; here it is (producing it) - I put my initials on it before it went out of my possession. I paid 4 s. for it.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Did there appear to be many books in the shop - A. It appeared to be well supplied with books.</p>

               <p>(The Libel was here read.)</p>
               <p>MR. FRENCH addressed the Court and Jury on behalf of the defendant, contending that while Unitarians (whose doctrines he considered highly blasphemous) were tolerated, by law, that it was unjust to prosecute persons in the prisoner's situation of life.</p>
